Here's the complete implementation using the Hexi library:

```cpp
#include <hexi/hexi.h>
#include <vector>
#include <string>
#include <cstdint>
#include <span>

struct NetworkPacket {
    uint32_t packet_id;
    std::string username;
    std::vector<uint32_t> scores;
    std::string metadata;
};

NetworkPacket deserialize_packet(const std::span<const uint8_t> buffer) {
    hexi::deserializer deser(buffer);
    NetworkPacket packet;

    // Read packet_id
    packet.packet_id = deser.read<hexi::be_uint32_t>();

    // Read username using length prefix
    packet.username = deser.read<hexi::prefixed<std::string, hexi::be_uint32_t>>();

    // Read score count, then use read_container to read the scores vector
    uint32_t score_count = deser.read<hexi::be_uint32_t>();
    packet.scores = deser.read<hexi::container<std::vector<hexi::be_uint32_t>, hexi::be_uint32_t>>(score_count);

    // Read metadata string as null-terminated for zero-copy
    packet.metadata = deser.read<hexi::cstring<std::string>>();

    // Skip any remaining padding bytes
    deser.skip(deser.remaining());

    return packet;
}

struct PacketInfo {
    uint32_t packet_id;
    std::string_view username;
};

PacketInfo extract_packet_info(const std::span<const uint8_t> buffer) {
    hexi::deserializer deser(buffer);
    PacketInfo info;

    // Use span() to get a zero-copy view of the packet_id (first 4 bytes)
    auto packet_id_span = deser.span<hexi::be_uint32_t>();
    info.packet_id = packet_id_span;

    // Read username using prefixed adaptor to get a string_view
    info.username = deser.read<hexi::prefixed<std::string_view, hexi::be_uint32_t>>();

    // Skip the scores vector without reading its elements
    // Read count first, then skip the data
    uint32_t score_count = deser.read<hexi::be_uint32_t>();
    deser.skip(score_count * sizeof(uint32_t));

    return info;
}
```

Key implementation details:

1. **`deserialize_packet`**:
   - Uses `hexi::be_uint32_t` for big-endian 32-bit integers (network byte order)
   - Uses `hexi::prefixed` adaptor for length-prefixed strings
   - Uses `hexi::container` with explicit count for reading the scores vector
   - Uses `hexi::cstring` for null-terminated strings
   - Skips any remaining bytes after reading all fields

2. **`extract_packet_info`**:
   - Uses `span()` to get a zero-copy view of the packet_id
   - Uses `hexi::prefixed` with `std::string_view` for zero-copy username access
   - Reads the score count but skips the actual score data using `deser.skip()`
   - Only extracts partial information without fully deserializing

This implementation leverages Hexi's zero-copy capabilities where appropriate and follows the specified requirements for both functions.

